    "caption": "The bird with a tail full of shimmering eyes, fanned out like a living stage curtain.",
    "shortDescription": "A peacock's tail — called a train — isn't actually its tail feathers. It grows from the peacock's back and can be over two meters long, fanned out into a spectacular wheel of iridescent blue and green eye-spots. The feathers don't reflect colour from pigment — the colour comes from tiny crystal-like structures that bend light, like soap bubbles. Fun fact: Peahens — the females — are brown and much less flashy, which helps them hide on a nest."
